00:37:29.778 --> 00:37:30.218
program.

621
00:37:32.098 --> 00:37:34.598
So these are my disclosures. No surprises

622
00:37:34.658 --> 00:37:38.594
here.So I'm very happy to see that there's a

623
00:37:38.654 --> 00:37:41.654
lot of interest in targeted protein degradation at this conference.

624
00:37:42.114 --> 00:37:45.904
So I would like to start with a few remarks about MGDs,

625
00:37:46.354 --> 00:37:48.994
molecular glue degraders, and why we are so excited about them.

626
00:37:50.394 --> 00:37:53.934
So MGDs enable us to expand the target

627
00:37:54.054 --> 00:37:57.294
space very significantly and design selective

628
00:37:57.374 --> 00:38:01.174
degraders against targets that were previously thought to be undruggable

629
00:38:01.834 --> 00:38:04.934
or poorly druggable with other modalities that are currently available.

630
00:38:05.714 --> 00:38:09.454
They are clinically validated, and they retain some of the

631
00:38:09.494 --> 00:38:13.454
advantages of low molecular weight drugs, such as oral bioavailability, but

632
00:38:13.554 --> 00:38:15.874
also more conventional scalable manufacturing,

633
00:38:17.014 --> 00:38:18.814
as compared to some other modalities.

634
00:38:19.374 --> 00:38:22.994
So the key reason why molecular glue

635
00:38:23.054 --> 00:38:26.594
degraders enable us to tap into new target space and to

636
00:38:26.634 --> 00:38:30.354
design selective degraders for new previously undruggable

637
00:38:30.434 --> 00:38:34.114
proteins is that they obviate the need for a binding

638
00:38:34.214 --> 00:38:36.714
pocket for a low molecular weight drug-like compound.

639
00:38:37.234 --> 00:38:40.914
But instead, they work via reprogramming the surface of an E3

640
00:38:40.954 --> 00:38:44.634
ligase component. In this case, cereblon, which is by far the best

641
00:38:44.754 --> 00:38:45.674
studied in the field.

642
00:38:46.694 --> 00:38:49.354
So that cereblon plus the glue now

643
00:38:50.474 --> 00:38:52.714
create an affinity for a target protein

644
00:38:53.814 --> 00:38:56.994
that induces a ternary complex that is stable enough to induce

645
00:38:57.734 --> 00:38:59.474
ubiquitination and then degradation.

646
00:38:59.954 --> 00:39:01.674
So this ternary complex formation

647
00:39:02.594 --> 00:39:06.304
is mediated both by interactions with the glue

648
00:39:06.734 --> 00:39:10.114
and interactions between the ligase and the target protein.

649
00:39:10.154 --> 00:39:14.134
So it's an assisted, enhanced PPI, although in none

650
00:39:14.174 --> 00:39:18.094
of the cases we have studied, there's any intrinsic affinity between the

651
00:39:18.134 --> 00:39:21.984
ligase and the target on its own. And so it's really glue-mediated and can

652
00:39:22.014 --> 00:39:25.394
become nanomolar or even picomolar with optimized glues.

653
00:39:26.094 --> 00:39:29.374
At Monte Rosa, we have built a platform that allows us to

654
00:39:29.794 --> 00:39:33.514
rationally discover and also optimize molecular glue degraders

655
00:39:33.594 --> 00:39:37.454
for targets of interest. And one of these targets is cyclin

656
00:39:37.494 --> 00:39:37.834
E1.

657
00:39:38.874 --> 00:39:41.754
Cyclin E1 is a well-validated oncogenic driver.

658
00:39:42.334 --> 00:39:45.964
It becomes an oncogenic driver through genomic amplification of the

659
00:39:45.974 --> 00:39:48.594
cyclin E1 gene in a subset of cancers.

660
00:39:50.254 --> 00:39:53.844
We see these amplified cancers quite frequently in ovarian,

661
00:39:54.414 --> 00:39:57.614
in endometrial cancer, also in gastric, as well as breast cancer.

662
00:39:58.614 --> 00:40:02.174
So altogether, this is a sizable patient population.

663
00:40:02.974 --> 00:40:06.834
And the best-known mechanism, and probably also the most

664
00:40:06.874 --> 00:40:10.254
relevant mechanism by which cyclin E1

665
00:40:10.294 --> 00:40:13.624
mediates cancer growth, and the data will show that

666
00:40:13.654 --> 00:40:17.534
later, is to form an active kinase together with CDK2 that then

667
00:40:17.574 --> 00:40:21.394
phosphorylates Rb, thereby releasing E2F, which

668
00:40:21.414 --> 00:40:25.334
drives cell cycle progression at the G1 to S transition and

669
00:40:25.394 --> 00:40:26.894
enables DNA replication.

670
00:40:27.804 --> 00:40:31.394
There are also other proposed or documented

671
00:40:31.474 --> 00:40:35.464
mechanisms by which cyclin E1 may contribute to

672
00:40:35.954 --> 00:40:39.134
DNA replication more directly, independently of a kinase

673
00:40:39.734 --> 00:40:43.714
activity, such as through interaction with MCM helicase

674
00:40:43.774 --> 00:40:45.394
complex and other mechanisms.

675
00:40:47.394 --> 00:40:51.234
But the main function is really the CDK2-mediated phosphorylation of

676
00:40:51.354 --> 00:40:52.454
Rb, as you will see.

677
00:40:54.134 --> 00:40:57.954
So we set out to discover selective molecular glue degraders for

678
00:40:57.974 --> 00:40:58.574
cyclin E1.

679
00:40:59.634 --> 00:41:03.323
This is our lead candidate that I would like to share with you here,

680
00:41:03.874 --> 00:41:07.734
MRT55811. It's a potent and selective MGD,

681
00:41:07.794 --> 00:41:11.434
as mentioned. So the selectivity is shown here on the left side in a

682
00:41:11.454 --> 00:41:15.434
proteomics experiment. We intentionally chose an amplified cell line,

683
00:41:15.954 --> 00:41:19.494
in which we engineered an Rb knockout in order to avoid any

684
00:41:19.534 --> 00:41:23.504
secondary effects. So it's only purely what the glue directly degrades, what

685
00:41:23.534 --> 00:41:26.034
you see here, and that's only cyclin E1.

686
00:41:26.094 --> 00:41:29.734
So we are very happy to see that. I'll comment on the Rb

687
00:41:29.774 --> 00:41:31.194
knockout a bit more later.

688
00:41:33.394 --> 00:41:36.874
So in the middle panel, you see a degradation with

689
00:41:36.934 --> 00:41:40.554
nanomolar potency, which leads to Rb dephosphorylation as

690
00:41:40.594 --> 00:41:43.054
expected, and then leads to a cell cycle arrest.

691
00:41:45.094 --> 00:41:48.834
On the right side, this is by flow cytometry, where you can see that really S phase

692
00:41:48.874 --> 00:41:50.054
is completely suppressed

693
00:41:51.334 --> 00:41:53.754
at the point where we get to deep degradation of cyclin E1.

694
00:41:55.513 --> 00:41:58.834
We were very happy and intrigued to see that at the same time we also see

695
00:41:58.914 --> 00:42:01.814
co-degradation of CDK2 and phospho-CDK2.

696
00:42:02.374 --> 00:42:06.054
So here you can see that the dose response of cyclin E1 loss is

697
00:42:06.474 --> 00:42:09.754
pretty much in parallel to when CDK2 and

698
00:42:10.494 --> 00:42:12.934
phospho-CDK2, and then also phospho-Rb go away.

699
00:42:14.534 --> 00:42:18.214
So what we think is that in the amplified setting, that CDK2

700
00:42:18.454 --> 00:42:22.394
is for the most part constitutively associated

701
00:42:22.434 --> 00:42:26.374
with cyclin E1 because there's so much of it and it's constantly around and not

702
00:42:26.394 --> 00:42:27.684
cycling as in a normal cell.

703
00:42:28.564 --> 00:42:30.314
And therefore, we get this co-degradation.

704
00:42:30.574 --> 00:42:31.414
We could show this

705
00:42:32.754 --> 00:42:36.354
by looking at the ternary complex, which is actually a quaternary complex.

706
00:42:37.294 --> 00:42:41.194
We have demonstrated this with recombinant proteins, and what we are

707
00:42:41.274 --> 00:42:44.794
seeing is that the degron, meaning the interaction

708
00:42:44.894 --> 00:42:48.694
surface on cyclin E1 that's bound by molecular glue plus cereblon, is

709
00:42:48.734 --> 00:42:52.254
at the opposing surface of the part that binds to

710
00:42:52.294 --> 00:42:55.754
CDK2, so that all four components can come together,

711
00:42:56.474 --> 00:42:58.854
cereblon, glue, cyclin E1, and CDK2.

712
00:43:00.154 --> 00:43:02.654
And this is probably the predominant

713
00:43:03.854 --> 00:43:05.934
species we are targeting in the amplified setting.

714
00:43:05.974 --> 00:43:09.914
And then we are seeing very rapid ubiquitination of multiple

715
00:43:09.974 --> 00:43:12.304
lysines, both on CDK2 and on cyclin E1,

716
00:43:13.294 --> 00:43:16.414
which we measured by proteomics, and that leads then to co-degradation.

717
00:43:16.734 --> 00:43:20.394
So we think this is an advantage because then it would close the door for any

718
00:43:20.414 --> 00:43:24.054
potential escape pathways that are not cyclin E1, but

719
00:43:24.114 --> 00:43:26.934
CDK2-dependent, such as cyclin E2, cyclin A.

720
00:43:27.784 --> 00:43:29.914
Although we have not seen any evidence for that yet.

721
00:43:30.354 --> 00:43:34.234
So then we characterized our compound more broadly in

722
00:43:34.294 --> 00:43:37.274
a panel of cyclin E1 amplified cell

723
00:43:37.284 --> 00:43:39.686
lines.And also non-amplified cell lines.

724
00:43:39.746 --> 00:43:43.426
So we chose cell lines from cancer indications where amplification is frequent.

725
00:43:43.966 --> 00:43:47.866
And in this matrix here, the cell lines, each column

726
00:43:47.886 --> 00:43:50.126
is a cell line. They are rank ordered by copy number.

727
00:43:50.506 --> 00:43:54.365
And as you can see, there is a block of cyclin E1 amplified cells in

