1617
01:37:14.304 --> 01:37:18.124
RAS is a small GTPase that toggles between a GDP-bound

1618
01:37:18.344 --> 01:37:20.924
off state and a GTP-bound on state.

1619
01:37:21.724 --> 01:37:24.724
In normal cells, this is tightly regulated to control cell growth.

1620
01:37:24.924 --> 01:37:28.564
Mutations in RAS, particularly at G12, G13, and Q61,

1621
01:37:29.144 --> 01:37:32.744
lead to accumulation of RAS in the on state, and this drives excessive

1622
01:37:32.864 --> 01:37:34.904
signaling and uncontrolled growth.

1623
01:37:34.944 --> 01:37:38.684
And this is the main driver of RAS-addicted cancers, which are some of the

1624
01:37:38.724 --> 01:37:40.744
most devastating of human cancers.

1625
01:37:43.984 --> 01:37:47.624
Under normal conditions, RAS is activated in response to growth factors, which

1626
01:37:47.664 --> 01:37:50.644
promote the GEF-mediated exchange of GDP for GTP.

1627
01:37:51.064 --> 01:37:54.324
This leads to a conformational change in RAS that allows it to now interact with

1628
01:37:54.384 --> 01:37:57.624
downstream effectors and drive signaling and then growth and

1629
01:37:57.684 --> 01:38:01.344
proliferation. RAS is inactivated by hydrolysis of the bound

1630
01:38:01.424 --> 01:38:04.854
GTP back to GDP, and this is stimulated by

1631
01:38:05.344 --> 01:38:08.204
endogenous GTPase activating proteins or GAPs.

1632
01:38:09.944 --> 01:38:10.984
Oops, sorry, wrong way.

1633
01:38:12.104 --> 01:38:15.754
Oncogenic mutations in RAS disrupt this regulation and, in a majority of

1634
01:38:15.804 --> 01:38:18.464
cases, disable this GAP-mediated hydrolysis.

1635
01:38:19.084 --> 01:38:23.054
This leads to accumulation in the on state, and hence uncontrolled cell growth and

1636
01:38:23.124 --> 01:38:25.964
proliferation, which is underlying the cancer.

1637
01:38:27.064 --> 01:38:29.744
Oops, I'm going the wrong way. Sorry.

1638
01:38:29.824 --> 01:38:32.784
Thus far, there's really been two major classes of RAS inhibitor.

1639
01:38:33.364 --> 01:38:35.084
The first class is the RAS off inhibitors.

1640
01:38:35.124 --> 01:38:38.924
These are switch two pocket binders that bind preferentially to the off state, and

1641
01:38:38.964 --> 01:38:42.604
the pioneers of this class being sotrastaurin and adagrasib, and they lead to

1642
01:38:42.644 --> 01:38:45.824
accumulation of RAS in this or they trap RAS in this inactive

1643
01:38:46.364 --> 01:38:50.316
state that is incompetent for signaling.The other class of inhibitors is

1644
01:38:50.326 --> 01:38:52.806
the molecular glues or tricomplex inhibitors.

1645
01:38:53.076 --> 01:38:55.336
These bind exclusively to the on state of RAS.

1646
01:38:55.876 --> 01:38:59.616
They do so by engaging with an endogenous chaperone protein called cyclophilin

1647
01:39:00.136 --> 01:39:04.116
that then forms a neomorphic protein interface that binds to GTP-bound

1648
01:39:04.196 --> 01:39:07.916
RAS. The formation of this tricomplex sterically occludes RAS

1649
01:39:07.956 --> 01:39:11.596
interaction with downstream effectors, as exemplified here with an

1650
01:39:11.676 --> 01:39:12.696
overlay with CRAF.

1651
01:39:13.696 --> 01:39:17.476
Today, I would like to introduce a third class of inhibitors. Oh, my goodness.

1652
01:39:18.616 --> 01:39:22.376
That basically catalytically inactivate RAS and then

1653
01:39:22.556 --> 01:39:26.476
essentially stimulate the hydrolysis of RAS GTP to RAS GDP

1654
01:39:26.496 --> 01:39:29.936
and mutant RAS, and in so doing, mimic the activity of

1655
01:39:30.216 --> 01:39:31.976
natural gaps at wild-type RAS.

1656
01:39:33.496 --> 01:39:37.036
So one might ask, why do we need yet another class of RAS inhibitor given that we

1657
01:39:37.096 --> 01:39:39.516
already have off and the on inhibitors?

1658
01:39:40.116 --> 01:39:43.696
And I think that while there are a varied number of different types of

1659
01:39:43.736 --> 01:39:47.286
molecule there with different mutant selectivities and different features, and

1660
01:39:47.336 --> 01:39:51.136
several of those are already providing nice clinical benefit to patients, perhaps

1661
01:39:51.236 --> 01:39:54.856
most recently exemplified by the data we released last week with

1662
01:39:54.896 --> 01:39:58.696
deraxone rasip in our RASloot 302 study in pancreatic cancer.

1663
01:39:59.436 --> 01:40:02.336
But RAS is a challenging target, I think, as many of you know, and

1664
01:40:03.196 --> 01:40:07.006
we need to come forward with multiple therapeutic options to offer long-term

1665
01:40:07.096 --> 01:40:10.596
benefit to patients. In particular, it's now emerging under

1666
01:40:10.616 --> 01:40:14.336
therapeutic pressure from both RAS on and RAS off inhibitors that these

1667
01:40:14.436 --> 01:40:18.036
tumors escape by reactivating oncogenic RAS signaling.

1668
01:40:18.616 --> 01:40:22.556
This is exemplified here by some data from our own phase one two study with

1669
01:40:22.576 --> 01:40:26.456
